export const batch129 = {
  'dont-forget-your-crown.json': {
    base: { id: 'dont-forget-your-crown', title: "Don't Forget Your Crown", author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781616736316 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Common myths let men off the hook for bad behavior',
        text: "In any partnership, your partner's mindset shapes the relationship, and many men fall short. Worse, they invent reasons for treating women poorly, and other men copy those reasons. These so-called reasons are myths, and this chapter breaks them apart.\n\nThere are plenty of excuses and very little effort to change.\n\nThe first myth says a man will act right for the right woman. This claim is almost always false. It assumes that bad behavior is a shield he uses when he feels scared. A man who treats you well chooses to grow on his own and chooses to grow for you as well.\n\nReal change starts with a deliberate choice to do better.\n\nA second myth claims that every man cheats, and a faithful man is rare. This is another story used to excuse harm. Cheating is not something people are born to do. No one is wired to be unfaithful. When a man loves you, he stays true. Modern culture has pushed this story so hard that many people accept it. The belief that cheating happens even in loving partnerships is wrong and damaging.\n\nMany women stay in unhappy partnerships because they accept this story. They take infidelity and disrespect as part of the deal. That is not the way love works. A serious commitment should be free of disloyalty.\n\nLoyalty is a daily choice, not a switch you can flip on later.\n\nThe last myth is the worst. It says men love confident women. That sounds nice, but it is rarely true. Many men feel threatened by confidence and work hard to break it down. When a man meets a confident woman, his ego is hurt, and he sees her as a challenge to his sense of power.\n\nSo he spends his time trying to shrink her. Once she is under his thumb, he feels in control. Confident women often end up single or with men who chip away at their confidence through gaslighting and sly insults.\n\nThis summary will help you see why self-respect comes first. You will also learn to spot the excuses sleazy men use, so you can ignore them and stop chasing a man who does not deserve you.\n\nMany women live with unfaithful or abusive partners and stay out of fear of stigma or because they share children with them."
      },
      {
        title: 'Knowing when to walk away can save your life',
        text: 'Many women hesitate to leave partnerships that have become unhappy, or that were unhappy from the start. There is a social cost when a woman leaves, especially a marriage, because people see it as her failure to keep a man. Society has trapped women in situations that hurt them, or worse, put their lives at risk.\n\nSociety has left women with few choices about how they should be treated.\n\nLearning to walk away is a skill that needs practice and readiness. Men who know a woman will be judged for leaving often make things worse. The result is more harm, both verbal and physical.\n\nWhen you accept bad treatment, you open the door to worse.\n\nWhen a man treats you poorly, it is not because he does not know better. He knows there are no consequences. Let him get away with it once, and he will try again. Forgive him when he hurts you, and he will test how much more you can take. If he wants to push the limit, he will not stop until you stop him.\n\nNo one else will guard your happiness and safety. Take that step today.\n\nWhen there is abuse or mistreatment in a relationship, you have to speak up about his actions. If he keeps going, find the door and use it. Your happiness is not up for debate. You have to speak for yourself. Staying quiet is not an option, because your happiness belongs to you.\n\nA man who shapes up only for the right woman is a false idea, and a harmful one to keep spreading, as Derrick Jaxn has written.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The relationship and sex dynamic takes work',
        text: 'Sex plays a big role in modern relationships. It gets hyped and treated like a prize. Some people enter relationships just to have sex, and some have sex just to feel something. People put on masks, lie, and scheme to get what they want. That kind of behavior cheapens the place of real intimacy in a relationship.\n\nPutting sex on a pedestal can make you desperate for it.\n\nThis pressure has given rise to many strategies for the early stages of dating. Some women hold back sex during the talking stage to test a man. This tactic can work, but some men are patient, and that patience is not always a good sign. Once he knows you are playing this game, he will simply wait you out.\n\nHealthy partnerships grow through give and take.\n\nSome men wear a good-guy mask long enough to get what they want, then disappear. Watch out for the self-styled good guy. He is a narcissist who believes sex is owed to him. A good man wants to know you first and to share himself with you before sex happens, on both sides. If he has to trick you to get in your bed, you should be careful. If you sense he is only after sex, trust your gut and walk away.\n\nIn a new relationship, sex should grow out of shared interest and shared intention.\n\nDo not assume a man is good just because he was charming on the first date. Pay close attention to how he acts, speaks, and thinks at other times, not only when you are dressed up for dinner.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Common mistakes to skip in new relationships',
        text: 'Women make a lot of early mistakes in dating, and those mistakes can lead to big problems later. The cause is often past heartbreak or a fear of being alone. Men will pick up on that fear nine times out of ten if you let them.\n\nNever let your need for a partner show on the first few dates.\n\nFirst, do not assume he is a nice guy on early dates. If he keeps saying he is, watch out. He is trying to convince you and himself. Time will show who he really is, so pay attention and you will see the changes.\n\nDo not judge a person until you have watched them for a long stretch.\n\nSecond, do not put up with even a hint of bad behavior. If you let it slide, it will grow. If he is rude to the waiter or the valet, he will be worse to you. Small things you ignore often turn into bigger problems. Cut off bad behavior the moment you see it.\n\nDo not make excuses for bad behavior. Address it right away.\n\nThird, never make excuses for his flaws. If he said or did something wrong, do not justify it. He is probably watching to see what he can get away with. Remember your worth and decide how you want to be treated.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A wedding will not fix a broken relationship',
        text: 'Marriage can be a beautiful thing, the natural next step after months or years of steady love. It should happen because two people in love decide to build a life together.\n\nMarriage works best after a steady and happy partnership.\n\nIt should not come from pressure or panic. You both need a clear picture of what you want. Some people think marriage is a quick fix for a struggling relationship, and they jump in and regret it later.\n\nA long-term promise to a bad partner will not change who they are.\n\nWhen a relationship starts to fail, some people want to lock it down with a wedding. That only deepens the crisis. People say marriage will make him treat you better or finally step up. That is not true. Marriage can make things worse.\n\nA bad relationship leads to a bad marriage. Do not walk into a bad situation out of fear.\n\nA wedding gives a man a sense of control. If he has been mistreating you, marriage only confirms his habits. Marriage also makes it harder to leave, because ending a marriage means a messy divorce, while dating can just stop.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Loyalty is the foundation of every healthy relationship',
        text: 'In any partnership, trust and loyalty matter more than anything. Do not accept the lie that loyalty is hard or even impossible for men. It is not, and the lie is just an excuse for cheating. A healthy relationship rests on fidelity.\n\nLoyalty is not rare. Demand it without apology from any partner.\n\nWhen a relationship lacks loyalty, many things fall apart. A cheating partner chips away at the other person self-esteem and makes her question her own worth. That kind of damage can spread to her work and her life.\n\nWithout loyalty, there is room for chaos and pain.\n\nWithout loyalty, there is no trust. Without trust, there is no love. A relationship full of betrayal becomes empty, exhausting, and harmful. Nothing real can grow in that kind of soil. Stay away from a chronic cheater, and never put up with betrayal when it shows up.\n\nIf you spot bad behavior early on, speak up and push for change. If he cannot or will not change, do not commit to him. You deserve a partner who takes you seriously and puts your well-being above his impulses. If he cannot drop a bad habit for you, he is the wrong person.\n\nA relationship without loyalty has no love in it, and it will only turn toxic.\n\nWhen you start a new relationship, or when you are already in one, make sure loyalty sits at the center of it. Without loyalty, there is no love, and without love, there is only hurt and harm. Do not accept that. Remember, your worth is not up for grabs.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Dating has become a battlefield for women. They have to come up with clever plans to win. The prize is a real relationship. Men, on the other hand, can do very little and still be seen as the prize that women must chase. That setup means a man can act any way he wants and still find a partner, while women have to clear hurdle after hurdle. This has to change. Women have to rediscover their worth and take back their power.\n\nThey have to ask for what they want without shame. They need honest, open talks about how they expect to be treated, both before and during the relationship. They need partners who take the lead in doing better, not partners who shrug it off. To take back their power, women have to watch out for men who try to chip away at their confidence or crush their self-esteem.\n\nSome men hide behind a good-guy mask and are not good at all. Women need to reject the idea that cheating is a right reserved for the right woman, and they need to demand loyalty from their partners. Remember, a wedding will not fix a bad relationship. If a partner will not change, a ring will not work magic on him.\n\nTelling someone to leave the past behind is a sign that he does not want to hear about the painful experiences that shaped how she moves through relationships. It is the language of weak men, as Derrick Jaxn has written.\n\nIf the man you are with makes you doubt yourself, picks at you, and gaslights you, you are with a narcissist, and you need to leave now.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'dopamina-el-arma-secreta-contra-el-envejecimiento.json': {
    base: { id: 'dopamina-el-arma-secreta-contra-el-envejecimiento', title: 'Dopamine', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781616815380 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A modern take on aging',
        text: 'Picture an hourglass that starts running the moment you are born. The image captures what aging feels like, but aging is more than a physical process. It also touches our emotions and our minds.\n\nWhen we work actively on aging, we can add years to our life and life to our years.\n\nWhy do we age in the first place? Many factors play a role, including genetics. Most experts point to the slow breakdown of cells and organs as the main cause.\n\nOther factors include chemical changes in DNA over time, the build-up of damaged proteins, and shifts in how the body handles nutrients. Knowing these factors helps us slow aging down, or even roll some of it back.\n\nDifferent species and different people age at different rates. If that were not true, we could share long lives with the people we love. Aging is complex and has been shaped by evolution over thousands of years.\n\nResearchers are still looking for new ways to slow it down, but more studies confirm two powerful levers: our mindset and our daily habits. People who stay positive and move their bodies tend to age more slowly. Pair that with the wild card we will get to, and you have a real shot at slowing aging down.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The fear of getting older',
        text: 'Many people believe women live longer than men, but is that true? The World Health Organization points to social factors, like smoking and drinking, that help explain the gap. Men also take more risks, have twice as many car accidents, four times as many violent deaths, and seventy-five percent more suicides.\n\nManuel Collado, an expert in aging and stem cells, points to a biological reason as well. Patterns show up in animals and in humans, and the differences between male and female sex hormones play a role in how long we live.\n\nAging creeps up on us. It shows itself in weight gain, in wrinkles, and even in holding a phone farther away to read a text.\n\nPlato once wrote that sickness is early old age, and old age is permanent sickness.\n\nThe fear of getting older is real, and the search for a longer youth is on many wish lists. Most of us have felt uneasy about growing old, about looking wrinkled in the mirror, or about losing the energy we had in our younger years. The fear of aging travels with the fear of death that most people carry.\n\nThanatophobia, the fear of death, is common and can keep people from living fully.\n\nAs we grow older, the search for the secrets of staying young picks up. We wonder why some older adults stay strong while others face illness or disability. The next key points offer a possible answer.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The ticking clock inside us',
        text: 'Picture the hourglass again, with sand moving from one side to the other the moment we are born. That image is a useful way to think about aging, but aging goes beyond the body. It also reaches our emotions and our minds.\n\nWhen we take an active role in how we age, we can stretch our years and make those years better.\n\nWhy does aging happen at all? Many forces are at work, including the genes we inherit. Most experts point to the slow wearing down of cells and organs as the main cause.\n\nOther forces include chemical changes in our DNA over time, the build-up of damaged proteins, and the way our bodies manage nutrients. Knowing this helps us slow aging, or even turn some of it back.\n\nSpecies and people age at different speeds. If that were not the case, we could share long, full lives with the people we love. Aging is complex and has been shaped by evolution across thousands of years.\n\nResearch continues, but more studies confirm two powerful levers: mindset and lifestyle. People who stay positive and active tend to age more slowly. Add the wild card we will look at next, and you have a strong chance of slowing aging down.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Dopamine, the wild card of life',
        text: 'The human brain is a marvel of efficiency. Its neurons form an intricate web and pass messages to each other through chemicals. In a small piece of brain tissue, billions of neurons form as many links as there are stars in the Milky Way. It really is like having a universe in your head.\n\nInside that system, the star player is dopamine. Think of it as the wild card that wins the game of joy and youth. This so-called pleasure hormone drives motivation, attraction, humor, and joy. It also reaches the heart, kidneys, immune system, and other parts of the body, so its role is wide and complex.\n\nDopamine shapes our sense of pleasure and reward, and also our ability to picture the future and make choices.\n\nDopamine pushes us to chase rewards and learn from our actions, and it shapes how we imagine and decide. Before we act, we picture different options in our minds and try to guess what will happen. Dopamine tunes that picture, which helps us make better choices and avoid mistakes.\n\nWhen dopamine runs low, the result can be depression, which is more common in older adults. It is a bit like a forest fire that gets out of control. Aging affects more than the brain. It also wears down the immune system, so older adults have a harder time staying healthy.\n\nBrain neurons are connected by close to one hundred thousand kilometers of nerve fibers, and they use only as much energy as a fifteen-watt light bulb. Picture a small room lit up by the mind.'
      },
      {
        title: 'How dopamine shapes who you are',
        text: 'Human personality is a puzzle of behaviors, thoughts, and feelings, and it shifts from person to person. Dopamine adds another layer because it weaves through many parts of the brain, including the hippocampus, the striatum, and the cerebral cortex, and shapes many of our functions.\n\nProfessor Colin G. DeYoung, who teaches psychology at the University of Minnesota, has argued that dopamine is central to understanding personality. According to DeYoung, it lights up our drive to explore the world and chase rewards, especially when the reward is not guaranteed. This is not just a human trait. In the animal kingdom, this drive shows up as two kinds of behavior: a defensive one in the face of the unknown, and an exploratory one that kicks in when a reward, like food or shelter, is within reach.\n\nDopamine also affects our ability to wait for a reward, our desires, our drive, and our wish to learn. Extraversion, a key personality trait, is closely tied to dopamine, because outgoing people tend to be more curious and bolder in their search for rewards.\n\nDopamine levels help predict how successful a person may be in the future.\n\nTraits like openness to experience and intellect are tied to the pleasure hormone. So is creativity, because dopamine tunes what researchers call reduced latent inhibition. That trait lets some people spot patterns and notice repeating details that others miss.\n\nDopamine also plays a part in impulsivity. There are four flavors of impulsivity: urgency, lack of perseverance, lack of premeditation, and a constant search for sensation. The last two are tightly linked to dopamine.\n\nA few more findings round out the picture. Higher dopamine levels are linked to extraversion, openness, intellect, and impulsivity, while lower levels can fuel aggression, anxiety, and depression in some people. Dopamine also helps researchers study Alzheimer disease, including the role of tau and beta-amyloid proteins in the breakdown of neurons.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Dopamine and living longer',
        text: 'By now it is clear that dopamine touches almost everything, and we have seen what happens when it runs low. That brings us back to the big question: can we slow aging and live longer? Joseph Knoll, a Holocaust survivor and award-winning scientist, spent his life studying the link between dopamine and aging, and his work points to an answer.\n\nKnoll discovered a molecule called deprenyl. It eased the symptoms of Parkinson disease, but it also did something surprising. It seemed to lengthen life. He turned it into a drug. In studies on rats, those given deprenyl lived much longer than rats given a placebo. No drug had ever pushed a species past its usual maximum lifespan.\n\nAs if that were not enough, deprenyl also improved the sexual performance of the rats and acted like a long-lasting aphrodisiac. Later, researchers suggested the same might apply to humans, because the brain structures that use dopamine are similar across many mammals.\n\nKnoll also found that deprenyl seemed to protect the brain from the kind of damage that comes with age. It turned on antioxidant enzymes that shield neurons from stress and inflammation.\n\nDeprenyl helps in Parkinson disease because it blocks the MAO-B enzyme.\n\nKnoll spent decades studying these so-called secondary enhancers and deprenyl as a longevity tool. He tested it on himself for years and stayed active until the end of his life.\n\nThe takeaway from a lifetime of work is that the longer you keep your brain at full speed, the longer and better your life will be, as Joseph Knoll put it.\n\nKnoll work faded from view, but its reach is hard to deny. There is real hope that we can protect dopamine neurons from aging, and that could matter a lot for how long we live.\n\nScientists are feeling hopeful about the fight against aging, but in the search for a longer life, we should not ignore what we control today: the daily habits that keep dopamine in balance.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Lifestyle shapes how we age. A positive mindset and a strong will to live can change the rate at which our bodies and minds wear down. If you have been feeling bored, stuck, or numb lately, we hope this summary is a spark that pushes you toward gradual change and fresh experiences.\n\nIt can take a lifetime to understand the human brain. Many puzzles still stump even the experts. The fight against aging keeps moving forward, and science is getting closer to longer lives year by year.\n\nTry these ideas. Carve out parts of your day for hobbies you have not done in a while, and go for that experience you have been planning. Cut back on social media and endless scrolling, and trade some of that time for meditation, music, and time with friends. If you have been feeling down or flat for a long time, think about seeing a therapist. A professional can give you tools that fit your situation. Keep learning new things. Stretching your mind keeps your brain sharp and active.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'dotcom-secrets.json': {
    base: { id: 'dotcom-secrets', title: 'DotCom Secrets', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781616894152 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Step one: pick exactly who you want to serve',
        text: 'You need to know your target market very well. Many businesses miss this point. Ask the average business owner who their market is, and they will say something like, I sell men clothes, so my target market is any adult man who can afford them.\n\nThat is too broad, and it is the reason many businesses fail, especially online.\n\nIf a business grows with a market that broad, two things happen. The owner never makes the most money possible, because they are not serving the right people. They also get worn out trying to please everyone. Running a business is hard, so do not make it harder by refusing to narrow your market.\n\nNot everyone is your customer. Pin this to your office wall so you never forget it.\n\nIn an online business, detailed targeting is not optional. Without it, you will struggle to write marketing messages that attract and nurture an audience. We will dig into ads and marketing soon, but first, let us get your audience right. Here is what to do.\n\nBuild a clear picture of your ideal customer. Write down the traits of the customer you want to work with. Who are they? What do they like? What are their pain points and passions? How much do they earn each year? Where do they live, or does location not matter? Use a notebook to capture all of it. The exercise can feel silly, but it can change your business in a big way.\n\nPull your ideal customers in with strong offers. Once you know who they are and where to find them, the rest gets easier. For example, if your business helps middle-aged wrestlers with skin care, you know a free skin care guide will be a good hook, because they are curious to try something new.\n\nNow you know how to find your ideal customers. The next chapters will show you how to build a value ladder and move customers up it, how to build a sales funnel that converts, and what it takes to run strong marketing campaigns.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Move customers up your value ladder step by step',
        text: 'Every business should have a dream result it wants to deliver to its ideal customers. Business is not mainly about products or services. It is about solving problems. A dentist solves dental problems, not just fixes teeth. A makeup artist is in the beauty business, not just putting on makeup. A barber is in the grooming business, not just cutting hair.\n\nDo you see the pattern? Many people let their product or service box them in, but to make the most money, you have to think bigger. Picture the highest result you could deliver, then build a value ladder around it. Not everyone can afford the top tier, and even those who can will not buy right away. You have to walk them up the ladder. A value ladder usually runs from bait, to value one, to value two or more, to the peak value, and then to a continuity program.\n\nThe bait pulls them in. It is usually free or nearly free but still useful.\n\nYou cannot just ask strangers to buy from you. You have to draw them in with a hook and a strong first offer.\n\nHere is an offline example. If you run a beauty salon, you could post an ad that says, anyone who comes in tomorrow gets a free hair treatment. That is the bait. When they show up, you can offer to sell a hair growth product to the people who need it, or you can offer to style their hair. That is a higher level at a price. Then you can offer makeup or manicure services. Your peak value could be a full beauty and hair care package. Not everyone will buy it, but if your ad brought in the right leads, some will. For a continuity program, you can offer an annual fee for all their treatments, or monthly payments. The goal is to turn them into repeat customers and build a steady income.\n\nThe value ladder works for any business. You just need to think it through and come up with offers your ideal market cannot turn down.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Meet your market where they already are',
        text: 'Most business owners do not have time to handle marketing on their own. There is too much to do, so they hand it to an in-house team or a marketing agency they trust. If you are in this camp, you have probably been told that online marketing, when done well, is more powerful than traditional marketing, but you do not know exactly why.\n\nThe secret is targeting.\n\nOnline marketing lets you get very specific about who you reach. For example, you can target mothers of children with autism who love medicine, read Psychology Today often, and have spent five to ten thousand dollars online in the last thirty days. You can be as specific as you want. People like to see messages that feel like they were written for them, and that is not possible with radio, TV, or print.\n\nBuild ads that speak directly to the people you want to reach.\n\nTwo secrets make ad campaigns work. First, research your market so well that you know it inside and out. Understand how your future customers act online and offline. Know where they gather, what their pain points are, and how your business can help. This understanding will help you shape your ad and, just as importantly, decide where to run it.\n\nSecond, make your visuals and headlines catchy enough to stop people in their tracks and earn the click. It is hard at first, but you learn by doing.\n\nAs Dan Kennedy has said, the business that can spend the most to win a customer wins.\n\nRussell Brunson is the author of this approach.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Successful online businesses master the traffic game',
        text: 'There are three types of online traffic, and most non-marketers do not know the difference. Paying close attention to each type is the secret to high conversions. The three types are traffic you own, traffic you control, and traffic you do not control.\n\nTraffic you own is the best kind. It is your email list, your followers, your readers, and your customers. You own it because you can reach them directly without paying Google, Facebook, or any other ad platform.\n\nHaving followers or an email list that you can reach at will saves you the cost of running ads.\n\nTraffic you control is any kind of paid traffic. If you run an ad on Facebook, you do not own that traffic, Facebook does. But you get to choose what you want the people in that traffic to do, so you can say you control it. For example, you can send them to a landing page, a blog post, or an online store. The catch is that you have to pay every time you need it, so it is smart to convert these leads into traffic you own. Ask for emails or phone numbers in exchange for something useful.\n\nTraffic you do not control just shows up. You do not own it and you do not control it. When someone searches on Google and your site appears, they might land on a blog post and either keep exploring or leave. You cannot control them. The same is true for social media, unless you are running an ad. Your goal with traffic you do not control and traffic you control is to turn them into traffic you own.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Get emails opened with the building blocks of persuasion',
        text: 'The average person is on ten to twenty email lists and gets email every day. Keep that in mind when you write to your subscribers.\n\nMany email formats work, but behind every strong email sequence are timeless principles of persuasion. Big companies hire expert copywriters to write their emails and earn high click-through rates. You may not have the budget for a copywriter, and that is fine. With practice, you can learn to write emails that get opened.\n\nYour subject line matters a lot. It is the first thing readers see, and they decide whether to open the email based on it. A subject line that sparks curiosity, stuns them, or promises something useful earns plenty of clicks.\n\nAfter the subject line comes the body. The best emails build a connection, because people like you, look forward to hearing from you, and buy from you when they can relate. Email is a great place to build that connection. Do not worry about being perfect. Be real and make your emails relatable. Are you writing to new freelancers? What lessons from your own journey can you share? How can you weave useful lessons into a story while pointing them to your offer without sounding like a sales pitch?\n\nTo avoid sounding salesy, help your audience see the problem they have and offer a solution, which can be your product or service.\n\nIt takes time to learn to persuade people to act, but the more you do it, the better you get. Some people wonder how often to send emails. Send as often as you can, ideally no more than once a day and at least once a week. This keeps you fresh in your reader mind without becoming annoying.\n\nRussell Brunson has said that a confused mind always says no.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Build sales funnels that match the needs of your audience',
        text: 'Do not jump straight into landing pages, ad copy, and hot offers. All of that matters, but it is not the first step. The first step is to figure out what kind of traffic you will send to your landing page. There are three kinds of traffic here.\n\nHot traffic is made up of people who already know you. They are your customers, followers, or email subscribers. They know your business and they like the value you offer. It is easy to get them to act. You do not have to do much. Just tell them the value of what you are offering, and they will jump on it.\n\nWarm traffic comes from people who have heard about you from someone else. For example, if a social media influencer talks about your product in a video and asks their followers to check you out, that is warm traffic. The same is true when someone recommends your product in a Facebook group or in a blog post because they used it and liked it.\n\nThe key to earning recommendations is to do good work.\n\nCold traffic is made up of people who do not know you at all, so you have to go out of your way to win them over with testimonials or free trials. If you are smart, you will send cold traffic to a different landing page than the other kinds.\n\nA 2019 report from Portent found that website conversion rates drop by an average of four point four two percent for every extra second of load time.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Your online reputation matters for sales. Before the average person buys from a business, they do a quick search to see what others have said. Imagine they find your business, and the top results are negative reviews from bloggers. That is bad for business. That is why you need to put work into making sure your online reputation is strong. You cannot control what others say, but you can control your service and the quality of your products. When you wow people, they feel grateful and leave good reviews on social media, on their blogs, or as testimonials. Fast customer service is another way to earn good reviews. There are many ways to offer support, and using social media as a customer service tool works well because it has two benefits. You can answer customers quickly, and you can build an audience for your company on the same channel. Social media can be part of your service tool kit, or the only tool you use, depending on where your business is and how much you can invest.\n\nIf you run a company blog, turn each page into a mini landing page. Use pop-ups to share your bait on every page. Your ideal customers will find the bait interesting, click, and convert from traffic you do not control into traffic you own.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'doughnut-economics.json': {
    base: { id: 'doughnut-economics', title: 'Doughnut Economics', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781616985597 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A new way to think about the 21st century economy',
        text: 'Since the start of the 21st century, economics students have called for a change in what they learn. They feel that current theories do not explain the crises we face. Climate change is one crisis, and the syllabus still reflects an industrial age, while the real world has gone digital.\n\nStudent protests started the conversation, but a boycott of lectures can only point to the problem. It cannot fix it. You can keep challenging the current setup, but at some point you have to offer an alternative. Doughnut Economics might be the answer we need.\n\nDoughnut Economics lays out seven key ways of thinking we need to embrace to build the economy of the 21st century.\n\nWe need a new economic story that fits the world we live in and offers a strong response to the biggest challenges of our time.\n\nLife expectancy has climbed from forty-eight years in 1950 to seventy-one years in 2010, but inequality has soared in the same time. The richest one percent now hold more wealth than the rest of the world combined. On top of that, the planet is heating up, and the United Nations has estimated that the global population will reach eleven billion by 2100.\n\nEconomists carry weight, and politicians listen to them when they make policies that touch lives. That is why we need to rethink economics, so 21st century economists can give better advice and push leaders to make choices that help everyone, not just a few. We will look at why and how to change how we measure success, how to fight rising inequality, and how to use wealth to fight ecological damage.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A better way to measure economic progress',
        text: 'Using GDP as the main measure of progress was the language of the 20th century. GDP hides the cost of producing the output a country brags about. In many cases, that cost is severe inequality and environmental damage. For example, a family of four earning ten thousand dollars a month might look wealthy, but if more than eighty percent of that money comes from one person, the outcome can be painful.\n\nIn earlier years, economics was about earning as much as possible. That mindset created a world where billionaires sit on piles of money while others starve. What we need is a yardstick that lets everyone thrive. A world that offers equal opportunity and respects the dignity of work. A world that builds safe communities and cares for the planet. Let us call that world the Doughnut to give it shape.\n\nThe idea of Doughnut Economics was first coined in 2011 by economist Kate Raworth to picture the goal of economics for the 21st century.\n\nThe 21st century goal of economics should be to meet the needs of every person while protecting the planet.\n\nThe Doughnut has two rings. The inner ring is the social foundation of life. It contains twelve basic needs of every person: enough food, a clean environment and clean water, a reliable power supply, good education, decent health care, good housing, decent work and income, social equity, a political voice, peace and justice, gender equality, and access to information.\n\nA shortfall happens when people fall below this social foundation and are pushed into survival mode.\n\nThe outer ring of the Doughnut is the ecological ceiling. It is the upper boundary we cannot cross if we want the planet to keep supporting life. Beyond that ceiling are climate change, biodiversity loss, pollution, ozone depletion, and other threats to life on the planet.\n\nWe have to keep everyone between the inner and outer rings of the Doughnut. That is the sweet spot.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Bringing every player in the economy to the table',
        text: 'The world is not static, and neither are its needs. We need to keep up with the changes the world has gone through. To restore balance to the global economy, we have to swap the characters that defined 20th century economics for new ones. Today economists decide what happens to world economies, so the script they are following has to change, and someone has to write a new one with new players who have clear needs and ambitions.\n\nThe current script was first written by Paul Samuelson when he designed the Circular Flow diagram in macroeconomics. The diagram shows how money moves around an economy. Over time, it became the basis for defining the economy itself. It painted a picture of an efficient market, the benefits of trade for both sides, the perfection of finance, and the idea that the common person is the problem.\n\nThe global crises of the 20th century opened our eyes to the flaws of that model. Money does not just flow between households and businesses in a closed loop, as the diagram suggests. There are leaks and injections from at least three outside sources: banks, government, and international trade.\n\nTheir interference means that only some of the money gets counted in the system. Over time, those blind spots lead to chaos.\n\nWe need a fairer model that brings all players to the table. This new model, the Embedded Economy, has these traits. A planet that supports life. Social bonds that support humanity. Support for the systems of a diverse economy. Recognition of the work done in households. A market that is powerful but wisely embedded. Room for the creativity of the commons. A state that is accountable. Financial services. Innovative businesses. Fair trade. And protection against the abuse of power.\n\nThis new model takes us beyond tracking the flow of income to understanding other forms of wealth the old model ignored.\n\nOur well-being depends on more than money. We need a safe planet, human connections, social capital, and physical health to flourish.\n\nThe Embedded Economy pushes us to look past market efficiency and to value the work of households, the state, and cooperative efforts.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Humans are more than just rational actors',
        text: 'Old economic theory painted people as solitary, calculating, competitive, and never satisfied. That portrait leaves no room for our humanity. At best, it turns us into robots that cannot change their programming. We have to change this image, because we will act the way we see ourselves.\n\nA new self-portrait lets us see ourselves as rational and complex.\n\nEmbracing our complexity opens the door to economies that let us live in the safe and just space of Doughnut Economics. There are five main areas where our self-image has to change to reach that goal. These shifts in mindset will bring us closer to global security and prosperity.\n\nFirst, we have to move from seeing people as purely self-interested to seeing them as social and giving. Observation of human behavior shows that we punish selfishness and reward cooperation. We like to share and dislike people who try to take an unfair advantage. The level of give and take varies across cultures, but the principle shows up everywhere.\n\nSecond, we have to accept that our values are not fixed, they are fluid. Since the 1980s, social psychologist Shalom Schwartz and his colleagues have surveyed people from many backgrounds in over eighty countries. They found that humans hold ten basic values that motivate us. Each value can show up when triggered, and we can move from one to another many times a day and across a lifetime.\n\nThird, no one exists in isolation. We need each other to thrive. Our world is interconnected. We have communication systems that tell us what people on the other side of the world are doing in real time. That knowledge shapes our behavior, and it shapes economic choices as well.\n\nFourth, we are approximating beings, not calculators. Psychologists have found more than one hundred and sixty cognitive biases. We feel more than we think. Policymakers need to keep that in mind when they try to change behavior.\n\nFifth, we do not stand above nature. We are a small part of the web of life. The old image of nature as a pyramid with humans on top has to give way to a web-like view. We are not rulers. We are participants in protecting and caring for our home.'
      },
      {
        title: 'An economy is more like an organism than a machine',
        text: 'Instead of the old binary view of supply and demand, we have to dig deeper to find the hidden factors. In the 1600s, when Isaac Newton asked why an apple falls from a tree, he did not worry about how the apple was formed. Economists have taken the same mechanical view of the economy. It is time to treat the economy as a living organism that grows and needs support.\n\nWe have to move from a narrow focus on supply and demand to understanding what drives people to produce and consume.\n\nEconomists need to see the economy as an apple tree, not just a falling apple. When we look at the economy as a whole, we will find hidden factors that shape the final result, the apple, or the GDP.\n\nAs Kate Raworth has put it, today economy is divisive and degenerative by default, and tomorrow economy must be distributive and regenerative by design.\n\nWhen we look past the surface, what we find will push us to nurture an economy that spreads value across the whole system instead of concentrating it in the hands of a few. We will also adopt practices that support the life-giving cycles of the Earth so that we can keep producing apples on a safe planet.\n\nTo make that shift, we need economists who treat the economy like a garden rather than a machine. Their tools will be gardening tools, not wrenches. They will not try to predict and control the economy, but to watch how things are moving and adjust policies to fit the direction of change. Rather than rushing in every time the economy shows stress, we should build diversity and redundancy so it can bounce back on its own.\n\nThe word economics was first used by the philosopher Xenophon in Ancient Greece, and it means the art of household management. His work, Oeconomicus, is a Socratic dialogue about household life and farming.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Tackling global inequality',
        text: 'Inequality is growing as automation takes over more of the economy. Some efforts have eased inequality within countries, but global inequality is still a huge problem. Over the last fifty years, planet-wide income has grown by fifty percent, which sounds good, but the gains have gone mostly to the richest. The poorest have seen only a small lift. That pushes people outside the rings of the Doughnut. The reason is that we have not yet seen ourselves as part of a single global community. What we do in one country affects people in another, and we are connected in more ways than we admit.\n\nSo far, global migration has been the biggest way wealth has spread.\n\nTake the example of people who move to high-income countries and send money home to family and friends in low-income countries. The open question is whether wealthy countries will keep welcoming these migrants. It is important that migration does not end up making income gaps worse instead of better.\n\nToday there are better ways to make sure overseas development assistance from rich countries to developing countries reaches the right people. Technology has made mobile banking possible, so people in extreme poverty can get funds directly.\n\nAs Kate Raworth has asked, when it comes to giving a basic income to the poorest people on the planet, the question is no longer how on earth, but why on earth not.\n\nBeyond spreading wealth, we have to work together to protect the life-giving systems of the Earth. Resources are not endless, even when we act as if they are. The planet is our common home, and each of us has to protect the part that is in our care, for the good of the world and for the generations that come after us.\n\nWe also need a platform for sharing knowledge, so that anyone, anywhere, can get the information they need to solve local problems. Solving problems creates wealth. Knowledge is a privilege many people do not have. As education spreads, the world will become a better, more thriving place to live.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Using wealth to slow ecological damage',
        text: 'Going green is no longer about looking wealthy. It is about survival. The story that economic growth will fix environmental problems in developing countries is not true. Take India, for example. Economic growth has not led to a cleaner environment there. We have to be intentional about ecological problems, because they will not fix themselves.\n\nIndustries are growing fast, draining the planet of resources and steadily ruining it in the process. People can be selfish and forget that Earth is our only home. Once we destroy it, we have nowhere else to go. To change course, we have to accept that the Earth is not our property, even when we treat it that way. We cause harm not only to ourselves but also to other living beings. Corporate greed is destroying natural habitats and pushing many species to the edge of extinction. Big companies in particular have to take responsibility for their actions and put real effort into repairing the harm they have caused.\n\nThe economic system of the industrial age was linear and degenerative, not cyclical and regenerative, and that led to the exhaustion of resources.\n\nWe have mined the Earth minerals and burned fossil fuels for over two hundred years without planning to give anything back. That goes against how nature works, because in nature everything that takes also gives back. In our case, we give back to pollution and degradation while making ourselves very rich. It is time to design new economic models that put the health of the planet into the equation.\n\nEfforts to push corporations to care about the environment have moved through stages. First, they did nothing. Then they did what paid off. When they could no longer look away, they reluctantly did their share. As environmental pressure grew, they started to focus on avoiding harm. The current stage is generosity. Generosity means committing to regenerative designs that keep us within the safe and just space of Doughnut Economics. We have to learn to cut down on waste of matter and energy by recycling, refurbishing, repairing, and reusing as much as we can.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'The shape of our future depends on the kind of economics we practice. Doughnut Economics offers a hopeful blueprint for spreading wealth fairly and protecting the environment. It tells us to set aside the linear view that measures growth only through GDP and to pay attention to other forms of wealth that matter for well-being.\n\nThe state of the world may make this goal feel out of reach, but we have to hold on to hope. We have already taken the first step by naming the problem. We know that the economics of the 20th century failed us and added to the damage. Now we have to commit to the proposed solution. We have what it takes to build back better.\n\nStudents of economics today should be encouraged to take up this new way of thinking and doing business, not the old methods that no longer serve us. The journey to a safe and just space starts with the recognition that every economy contributes to the safety of everyone. No one is isolated. We have to value the contribution of every stakeholder: households, the state, the market, and the commons. We have to help them work together to build economies that support life and let everyone flourish.\n\nWe have to start seeing the economy as an organism that needs us as gardeners, not as a machine that needs technicians. That is how we will build economies that support life without being hooked on GDP.\n\nDepending on where you are in the world, ask yourself what choices you can start making that will spread wealth more fairly and slow down the planet damage.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'drama-free.json': {
    base: { id: 'drama-free', title: 'Drama Free', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781649330406 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'How unhealthy family ties drain your happiness',
        text: 'Picture a Sunday evening. Your phone buzzes, and your stomach tightens because you know it is a family member about to dissect your life choices again, wrapped in concern but delivered with surgical precision. Does that sound familiar?\n\nWe are social beings, and we depend on the connections we build. When a relationship, especially a family one, turns sour, it does more than hurt emotionally. It drains your energy, messes with your sleep, and can even affect your physical health.\n\nHappy relationships lead to a peaceful and balanced life.\n\nEven families that look happy on the surface can struggle behind closed doors. Unhealthy relationships do not always involve abuse, violence, or cheating. Think of the family that looks perfect online, but every dinner turns into a passive-aggressive battlefield. Or the parents who only want what is best for you, yet manage to make you feel guilty for every choice you make on your own.\n\nUnhealthy dynamics can look like toxic conversations, pressure, neglect, disrespect, or constant drama. Living like that for years teaches people to fight and protect themselves rather than to enjoy being close.\n\nThe good news is that as an adult, you can change these patterns. It is not easy, but it is worth it. Read on to spot unhealthy dynamics, set healthy boundaries, and either heal your family ties or leave them with peace and grace.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Spotting dysfunction is the first step toward healing',
        text: 'It is hard to see the dark when you have lived in it for years. A child who grows up with an absent or neglectful parent may see that absence as normal. Only when they see a healthy family, where both parents show up, do they realize that something was missing in their own upbringing.\n\nA common defense for people in unhealthy families is to hide what is going on. They deny, keep secrets, carry shame, and argue rather than face the problem. You hear sayings like what happens in this house stays in this house, or we do not air our dirty laundry.\n\nAs Nedra Glover Tawwab has put it, the way people engage in the family is usually how they engage in the world.\n\nChildhood trauma wears many faces. It can come from years of moving around, from abuse by parents, or from harm done by other relatives.\n\nSo how do you know if this applies to you? You may have childhood trauma if you struggle with constant frustration, self-sabotage, mistrust, avoidance, trouble speaking up for your needs, or shutting down your feelings.\n\nLooking honestly at yourself helps you find and address more negative patterns. Spotting these tendencies helps you clear them out.\n\nDestructive behavior is like a weed. Even if the roots are deep, you can still pull them out.\n\nA good place to start is journaling. Then try these questions. When you made a mistake as a child, what happened? Did someone help you learn, or did you get shamed, blamed, or ignored? What does your body do when your parents call? Do you relax, tense up, or feel dread? What is one thing you wanted your parents to understand about you that they never seemed to get?\n\nIf you feel deep mental pain or thoughts that drag you into long stretches of sadness, please consider therapy. A therapist can help you understand your feelings and build new patterns.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Setting boundaries to take back your life',
        text: 'A dysfunctional relationship is not always about a parent with a drug problem or an aggressive sibling.\n\nA person can come from a loving, supportive family that turns toxic the moment they try something new. The moment they grow and mention moving to a new city for a job, they are suddenly accused of abandoning the family and being selfish. Parents start sending articles about crime rates in the new city and bringing up how close families are supposed to stay.\n\nFor many parents, letting their children make their own choices and their own mistakes feels terrifying, and they try to protect their kids at any cost. They may scold their child for picking a college in another state or for dating someone they do not approve of.\n\nOverprotective relationships can be a sign of codependency or enmeshment. These patterns build extremely close bonds where it is hard to tell personal needs apart or to meet them.\n\nA codependent relationship also means that one or more members depend on the others. If one of them tries to leave, the rest push them back, because they are breaking the safe setup they know. If you try to set a boundary, your family may respond with resentment and sadness, with shaming or blaming, with open disapproval, or with resistance to your change.\n\nSetting boundaries in a dysfunctional family brings up a lot of feelings at once. You may feel frustrated because your parents keep fighting, and afraid to leave because they could hurt each other. In that case, you feel like you have to be the mediator or the peacemaker. It is a hard spot. You love your family, but you cannot give up your own life to serve their needs.\n\nThe best way to help someone without giving up your time, money, or life is to set an example of how to love and care for yourself. That way, you are not lowering your own worth or letting people use you.\n\nSelf-love shows others that your time, feelings, and choices matter.\n\nSpotting codependency is hard if you live in it and treat it as normal. Ask yourself these three questions. Are you responsible for other people feelings? Do you change your plans because of someone else mood? Do you feel guilty when you do something just for yourself? If you said yes to any of them, you may be stuck in a codependent pattern. Setting boundaries is the key to a healthier, better future.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Real change takes time and effort',
        text: 'Breaking a dysfunctional pattern is tough. It is a bit like trying to change your handwriting after thirty years. It is technically possible, but it takes conscious effort every time you pick up a pen.\n\nSome people think it cannot be done, especially when children of alcohol-abusing or depressed parents are more likely to inherit the same habits. The longer a problem has passed from generation to generation, the harder it is to wipe out, especially without support from the people around you.\n\nPsychologists James Prochaska and Carlo DiClemente studied how people actually change. They found that people who are ready to break their destructive patterns move through five stages.\n\nThe first stage is pre-contemplation. You can sense something is wrong, but you cannot name it. Maybe you feel wiped out after every family gathering, or you catch yourself apologizing for things that are not your fault, but you cannot quite connect the dots. You feel stuck, hurt, and desperate for someone else to change.\n\nThe second stage is contemplation. You can see the problem and name it, but you do not know how to deal with it. Lightbulb moments happen here, like realizing your mother is manipulative, or your brother is a narcissist. Many people go to therapy to untangle the feelings and pain they have been carrying. Some get stuck here, because now that they see the problem, they have to act, and not everyone feels brave enough to take that step.\n\nIgnorance and denial let you stay in a destructive pattern. Awareness pushes you to change.\n\nThe third stage is preparation. You speak up about your needs and boundaries and ask others to change how they act. Telling a loved one that their comments about your looks are hurtful, for example, can push them to drop the habit.\n\nThe fourth stage is action. Your boundaries and your new self become visible. You are no longer content to say that you do not like someone attitude. You refuse to accept their behavior and show them they cannot treat you the same way. Assertiveness and confidence are the hallmarks of this stage.\n\nThe fifth stage is maintenance. Your new patterns are steady, but you may slip into old thoughts or behaviors. Maybe you pick up your father emotional burden again, or you catch yourself apologizing for setting a boundary. Be kind to yourself when it happens, because change is never perfectly steady, and you will need all the support you can get.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Surviving is not the same as thriving',
        text: 'Many people see dysfunctional relationships as completely terrible and impossible to fix. The world is not black and white, though. Sometimes we expect too much from our families, especially our parents, assuming that having children made them wiser and more caring.\n\nYou alone can make yourself happy.\n\nThriving, just like surviving, is a choice. You can see everyone as an enemy and the world as a hostile place where you have to fight for what is yours. That mindset will help you survive. Or you can choose to look at your worldview and reshape it, picking choices that make you happy outside of the dysfunctional pattern.\n\nWhen you try to fix a relationship, a few tips can speed up the impact. First, get ready for pushback. Being the first one to break a family negative behavior loop is hard. Be ready for your loved ones to resist. When you stop being the family emotional dumping ground, someone else may have to step up, and they will not thank you at first. Find support outside the family.\n\nSecond, become your own advocate. Build positive habits like confidence, speaking up for yourself, setting boundaries, and being assertive. Name and meet your feelings and needs. Do not fall into a victim mindset, because it keeps you in a negative loop.\n\nThird, balance action with patience. Be patient with results, but act now. Small steps bring big changes. Try one small boundary this week, like not responding to every family text right away, or saying I will think about it instead of an automatic yes.\n\nFourth, let go of the need to control outcomes. Accept others as they are and accept that they may never change. Even if you change your own mindset, your loved ones may choose to stay the same. Your mother may always be anxious. Your father may never learn to express feelings in a healthy way. Your sibling may keep being dramatic. That is okay, because your peace does not depend on their transformation.\n\nYou can create real change when you show your loved ones a better way, with grace and love. Even if it has never happened in your family, do not hold back from showing love and appreciation. Saying dad, I really appreciate how hard you worked to provide for us can sit next to dad, I need you to stop giving me unsolicited financial advice. Kindness always breeds kindness.'
      },
      {
        title: 'When leaving a relationship becomes an option',
        text: 'Some relationships are like a sinking ship. You can get off, or you can go down with it. If that rings true, you have probably tried everything to save the tie, including changing yourself, setting boundaries, speaking up about your needs, and refusing to settle. In the end, you cannot force people to want a healthy relationship.\n\nAs Nedra Glover Tawwab has written, honesty is not betrayal. It is courage. Stop softening your story and let the truth set you free.\n\nSociety often frowns on breaking up a family, especially when things look fine on the surface. Pulling away from one family member can lead to loops of self-blame and guilt. Other relatives can pile on with doubts and judgments. For many people, blood ties should never be broken. That belief is toxic, though, because it forces you to accept more abuse, neglect, indifference, pain, or violence.\n\nEstrangement from a family member unfolds in different ways. Some need a pause or a break, while others want to cut off contact completely. It depends on the pain, anger, or fear they feel. Some go low contact. They show up for the major holidays but do not take part in regular phone calls. Others pick a temporary separation, a year or two to heal and reassess. And some choose permanent estrangement, because the relationship is too damaging to keep.\n\nYour life is the choices you make.\n\nCutting ties with a family member does not mean you forgive them right away or that you will reconcile later. Forgive and forget does not work with childhood trauma or major family problems. Do not let guilt affect your well-being or your choices. Your life is worth more than your bloodline. You have to put your happiness and safety first, before you wait for loved ones to give it to you.\n\nForgiving someone you love is even harder when they refuse to see their own faults, or when they cannot understand how you feel. Be ready to forgive not because you want the relationship to continue, but because forgiveness will free you and give you the peace you want.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Try this',
        text: 'Now let us move from analysis to action. These steps will help you start building healthier boundaries and more peaceful family relationships, starting today.\n\nFirst, journal your relationship dynamics. Pick one family member you often struggle with. In your journal, write down the core challenges and be specific. Do not just write we argue. Detail what you argue about and how the arguments usually unfold.\n\nSecond, identify pain patterns. What scenes keep coming up that upset you the most? What specific behaviors from this family member set you off? List at least three examples, and focus on how those behaviors affect you.\n\nThird, recognize your role. Look honestly at how your own behavior may mirror that of your family member. Are you just as quick to get defensive, critical, or avoidant? Be brave enough to see your part in the dynamic.\n\nFourth, script your responses. Picture a common triggering scene. Write out exactly what you will say to hold your boundaries. Practice saying it out loud. It will be easier to respond calmly in the moment.\n\nFifth, run a self-compassion check-in. Healthy boundaries are hard, and you may face guilt or pushback. Every day, take a moment to recognize your effort and be kind to yourself. Remind yourself that putting your well-being first is not selfish. It is essential.\n\nYou deserve peaceful and fulfilling relationships. These steps will not magically fix everything, but they will help you take control of your interactions and build a more harmonious family life. Be patient with yourself, and celebrate every small win along the way.'
      }
    ]
  }
};
